From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: VyOS LS1046A CI <ci@vyos-ls1046a>
Date: Thu, 29 May 2026 05:30:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa1: M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 2 - true-ZC RX arm
 observability (xsk_zc_rx_armed counter, dormant reprogram read-side)

M3-3 step 7 (true zero-copy RX, spec sec 6.1.7) has a three-mechanism plan:
(1) Recognise XSK-pool-sourced FDs by matching fd->bpid against
priv->xsk_bpid[band]; (2) Recover the xdp_buff via xsk_buff_recv() on the
XSK chunk; (3) reProgram the FMan RX port's primary BPID to the XSK pool's
BPID at xsk_pool_attach() so FMan DMAs directly into XSK chunks.

Sub-increment 1 (patch 0093) landed mechanism 1's recognition arithmetic
(fd->bpid == priv->xsk_bpid[band]) as the strictly-diagnostic
xsk_zc_eligible RX-hot-path counter, proving the recognition test is sound
with zero datapath change.

Mechanism 3 is the hardware-risky step: spec sec 6.1.8 records three DUT
crashes from under-load XSK RX work (list_add free-list corruption in
xp_alloc(), a dcache_clean_poc paging fault, and a 52 s soft-lockup). Per
the de-risking cadence that landed the observational xsk_rx_branch (0083)
BEFORE the productive RX branch (0084), and xsk_zc_eligible (0093) BEFORE
this, sub-increment 2 lands ONLY the *read side* of mechanism 3 as an
attach-time observability counter -- it does NOT reprogram the FMan RX
port and does NOT touch the datapath. The actual MURAM/BPID reprogram
write plus the xsk_buff_recv() recovery (mechanism 2) become the
hardware-risky sub-increment 4, gated behind the FILL-ring-empty guard
audit (spec sec 6.1.8 item 5) and DUT-validated under load.

What 0094 does (three additive, datapath-neutral edits):

  - dpaa_eth.h: u64 xsk_zc_rx_armed; appended to the contiguous xsk_*
    counter block (after xsk_zc_eligible from 0093). 18th xsk_* counter.

  - dpaa_ethtool.c: "xsk_zc_rx_armed" appended to dpaa_stats_xsk[]
    (the value-emit loop is length-driven; no loop edit needed).

  - af_xdp_pool_main.c: at xsk_pool_attach() success -- AFTER the BMan
    pool is created and seeded, AFTER rcu_assign_pointer() publishes the
    pool and the NAPI context is bound, and AFTER xsk_pool_attach_ok++
    but BEFORE return 0 -- the flavor module compares the freshly-
    allocated dedicated XSK BPID (priv->xsk_bpid[queue_id]) against the
    kernel page-pool BPID that the FMan RX port is currently programmed
    to DMA into (priv->dpaa_bp->bpid). When the two differ (the normal
    case: the XSK pool got its own BPID), the band is "armed" for a
    future true-ZC reprogram -- record that fact in xsk_zc_rx_armed and
    emit a one-line dev_info documenting the current-vs-target BPID pair.
    This is the exact read that sub-increment 4's reprogram write will
    consume to decide the FMan port's new primary pool. NO fman_port
    write happens here.

Why this is byte-identical to mainline on default/vpp: the entire
af_xdp_pool attach path is only reached when a userspace AF_XDP socket
binds XDP_ZEROCOPY on a DPAA1 netdev, which never happens on the default
flavor (no XSK consumer) -- the counter stays 0 and the RX/TX datapaths
are untouched. Even on a future vpp flavor that binds XDP_ZEROCOPY, this
patch only *reads* two BPIDs already living in struct dpaa_priv and bumps
a counter; FMan continues DMAing into the kernel page pool exactly as
before, so copy-mode RX (patch 0089) is preserved bit-for-bit until
sub-increment 4 performs the reprogram.

Why it is the right next move: it makes the reprogram *target* arithmetic
observable from userspace (ethtool -S | grep xsk_zc_rx_armed) at attach
time, before any FMan MURAM write touches live hardware. A non-zero
xsk_zc_rx_armed after a bind proves the dedicated XSK BPID was allocated
distinct from the kernel pool BPID -- the precondition for the
sub-increment-4 reprogram to have a meaningful effect. A zero value after
a successful attach would mean the dedicated BPID collided with the
kernel pool BPID (a bman_new_pool() anomaly) and the reprogram must be
suppressed -- caught here, dormant, before it can crash the DUT.

Spec sec 6.1.7 true-ZC mechanism 3 (read side) + sec 6.1.11.

Signed-off-by: VyOS LS1046A CI <ci@vyos-ls1046a>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
@@ -315,6 +315,42 @@
 }
 
 priv->xsk_pool_attach_ok++;
+
+/*
+ * M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 2 (patch 0094): true-ZC RX arm
+ * observability -- the READ side of mechanism 3 (reprogram the
+ * FMan RX port's primary BPID), with NO datapath change.
+ *
+ * priv->xsk_bpid[queue_id] is the dedicated BPID just allocated
+ * by bman_new_pool() (step 3 above) and seeded with XSK UMEM
+ * chunks (step 4). priv->dpaa_bp->bpid is the kernel page-pool
+ * BPID that the FMan RX port is CURRENTLY programmed to DMA into.
+ *
+ * For true ZC, sub-increment 4 will reprogram the FMan RX port's
+ * primary pool from dpaa_bp->bpid to xsk_bpid[queue_id] (the
+ * hardware-risky MURAM write -- spec sec 6.1.8 records three DUT
+ * crashes from under-load XSK RX, so the write stays out of this
+ * patch). Here we only OBSERVE that the two BPIDs differ, i.e.
+ * the dedicated XSK pool got its own BPID and the reprogram would
+ * have a meaningful, distinct target. We bump xsk_zc_rx_armed and
+ * log the current-vs-target pair so the reprogram precondition is
+ * verifiable from userspace (ethtool -S | grep xsk_zc_rx_armed)
+ * BEFORE any FMan write touches live hardware.
+ *
+ * On default/vpp this path is unreached (no XDP_ZEROCOPY bind);
+ * even under a future ZC consumer FMan keeps DMAing into the
+ * kernel page pool, so copy-mode RX (patch 0089) is preserved
+ * bit-for-bit until sub-increment 4 lands the reprogram.
+ */
+if (priv->dpaa_bp &&
+    priv->xsk_bpid[queue_id] != (int)priv->dpaa_bp->bpid) {
+priv->xsk_zc_rx_armed++;
+dev_info(priv->net_dev->dev.parent,
+ "af_xdp_pool: qband %u armed for true-ZC RX (xsk_bpid=%d, fman rx port primary bpid=%u; reprogram deferred to sub-increment 4)\n",
+ queue_id, priv->xsk_bpid[queue_id],
+ priv->dpaa_bp->bpid);
+}
+
 return 0;
 
 err_unmap:
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
@@ -304,6 +304,23 @@
  */
 u64 xsk_zc_eligible;
 
+/* M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 2 (patch 0094): true-ZC RX arm
+ * observability -- the read side of mechanism 3 (FMan RX port
+ * BPID reprogram). Bumped once per successful xsk_pool_attach()
+ * when the dedicated XSK BPID (xsk_bpid[band]) differs from the
+ * kernel page-pool BPID the FMan RX port currently DMAs into
+ * (dpaa_bp->bpid) -- i.e. the reprogram that sub-increment 4 will
+ * perform has a distinct, meaningful target. Strictly diagnostic,
+ * mirroring xsk_rx_branch (0083) and xsk_zc_eligible (0093): it
+ * proves the reprogram-target precondition is satisfied BEFORE the
+ * hardware-risky MURAM write (sub-increment 4) touches live FMan.
+ * Unreached on default/vpp (no XDP_ZEROCOPY bind); even under a ZC
+ * consumer FMan keeps DMAing into the kernel page pool, so the RX
+ * datapath is byte-identical to mainline until sub-increment 4.
+ * Spec sec 6.1.7 true-ZC mechanism 3 (read side) + sec 6.1.11.
+ */
+u64 xsk_zc_rx_armed;
+
 /* M3-3b (patch 0086): FMan PCD capability bitmask snapshot taken
  * at probe via dpaa_fman_get_caps(). 0 on mainline ucode 106 ->
  * all fman_cc_tree_/fman_hm_/fman_pol_ helpers short-circuit
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_ethtool.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_ethtool.c
@@ -72,4 +72,5 @@
 "xsk_tx_zc_submit",
 "xsk_tx_conf_zc",
 "xsk_zc_eligible",
+"xsk_zc_rx_armed",
 };
